0	<text font="0" height="20" left="89" textpieces="0" top="156" width="745">Improving the Table Boundary Detection in PDFs by Fixing the Sequence Error</text>
 
0	<text font="0" height="20" left="372" textpieces="0" top="183" width="178">of the Sparse Lines</text>
 
0	<text font="1" height="17" left="284" textpieces="0" top="243" width="354">Ying Liu, Kun Bai, Prasenjit Mitra, C. Lee Giles</text>
 
0	<text font="1" height="17" left="282" textpieces="0" top="265" width="357">College of Information Sciences and Technology</text>
 
0	<text font="1" height="17" left="262" textpieces="0" top="286" width="398">The Penn State University, University Park, PA, 16803</text>
 
0	<text font="1" height="24" left="320" textpieces="0" top="303" width="282">{yliu, kbai, pmitra, giles}@ist.psu.edu</text>
 
0	<text font="2" height="16" left="230" textpieces="0" top="371" width="68">Abstract</text>
 
0	<text font="3" height="14" left="102" textpieces="0" top="410" width="342">As the rapid growth of PDF documents, recognizing the</text>
 
0	<text font="3" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="428" width="360">document structure and components are useful for docu-</text>
 
0	<text font="3" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="446" width="360">ment storage, classiï¬cation and retrieval. Table, a ubiqui-</text>
 
0	<text font="3" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="465" width="360">tous document component, becomes an important informa-</text>
 
0	<text font="3" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="483" width="360">tion source. Accurately detecting the table boundary plays</text>
 
0	<text font="3" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="501" width="360">a crucial role for many applications, e.g., the increasing</text>
 
0	<text font="3" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="519" width="360">demand on the table data search. Rather than converting</text>
 
0	<text font="3" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="537" width="360">PDFs to image or HTML and then processing with other</text>
 
0	<text font="3" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="556" width="360">techniques (e.g., OCR), extracting and analyzing texts from</text>
 
0	<text font="3" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="574" width="360">PDFs directly is easy and accurate. However, text extrac-</text>
 
0	<text font="3" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="592" width="360">tion tools face a common problem: text sequence error. In</text>
 
0	<text font="3" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="610" width="360">this paper, we propose two algorithms to recover the se-</text>
 
0	<text font="3" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="629" width="360">quence of extracted sparse lines, which improve the table</text>
 
0	<text font="3" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="647" width="360">content collection. The experimental results show the com-</text>
 
0	<text font="3" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="665" width="360">parison of the performance of both algorithms, and demon-</text>
 
0	<text font="3" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="683" width="360">strate the effectiveness of text sequence recovering for the</text>
 
0	<text font="3" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="701" width="156">table boundary detection.</text>
 
0	<text font="2" height="16" left="84" textpieces="0" top="757" width="117">1. Introduction</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="102" textpieces="0" top="774" width="342">Portable document format (PDF) is a widely used docu-</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="793" width="360">ment format. Although many researchers analyze PDF doc-</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="811" width="360">uments by converting them to other formats (e.g., image,</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="829" width="360">html), automatically identifying the PDF document logical</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="847" width="360">structures information and document components (e.g., ï¬g-</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="866" width="360">ures, tables, etc) are still challenging problems [2] because</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="884" width="360">of three main reasons: 1) extracted texts from PDF ï¬les are</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="902" width="360">non-tagged; 2) wrong text sequences are generated by the</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="920" width="360">text extraction tools; 3) new noises are caused by necessary</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="939" width="360">tools (e.g., OCR) when converting the PDFs into other for-</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="957" width="107">mat (e.g., image).</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="102" textpieces="0" top="975" width="342">Tables, as a speciï¬c document component, are ubiqui-</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="993" width="360">tous everywhere. To thoroughly analyzing the table con-</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="1011" width="360">tent, locating the table boundary in a document is the ï¬rst</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="1030" width="360">and crucial step for consequent applications (e.g., the table</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="1048" width="360">search). Because most of the tables in scientiï¬c documents</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="84" textpieces="0" top="1066" width="360">are text-based tables, solely analyzing the text objects in</text>
 
=======================================COL========================================
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="373" width="360">a PDF ï¬le can achieve good performance in terms of sav-</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="392" width="360">ing efforts on other objects. However, existing text extrac-</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="410" width="360">tion tools face a common problem: the extracted text pieces</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="428" width="360">follow a different sequence from its original appearance in</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="446" width="360">PDF ï¬les. Although the wrong sequence does not affect</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="465" width="360">the PDF documents displaying for browsing purpose, it can</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="483" width="360">severely interfere the document content analyzing works</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="501" width="360">that rely on the information of the relative location and se-</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="519" width="360">quence among the text pieces. Table boundary detection is</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="537" width="360">a typical example. In order to improve the accuracy of the</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="556" width="360">table boundary detection, we need to recover the extracted</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="574" width="360">text sequences to the orders that comply with the humanâ€™s</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="592" width="360">reading habit. The sequence errors can be classiï¬ed into two</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="610" width="360">types: within-table errors and beyond-table errors. In this</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="629" width="360">paper, we propose two text sequence recovering algorithms</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="647" width="360">to ï¬x them. Our algorithms start with the detected sparse</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="665" width="360">lines in each PDF page and detect the table boundaries by</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="683" width="360">analyzing the sparse areas and the caption information. The</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="701" width="360">detail of the sparse line detection is out of the scope of this</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="720" width="354">paper. If interested, the details can be found in [3] and [4].</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="496" textpieces="0" top="738" width="342">The rest of the paper is organized as follows. Section 2</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="756" width="360">gives the deï¬nition for main terms used in this paper. Sec-</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="775" width="360">tion 3 elaborates two text sequence error categories. Section</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="793" width="360">4 introduces two text sequence recovering algorithms and</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="811" width="360">how to detect the table boundary based on the recovered se-</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="829" width="360">quences. Section 5 demonstrates the experimental results.</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="848" width="326">Conclusion and future work are included in section 6.</text>
 
0	<text font="2" height="16" left="478" textpieces="1" top="889" width="157">2  Term Deï¬nitions</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="496" textpieces="1" top="910" width="342">Free online dictionary1deï¬nes a table as an orderly ar-</text>
 
0	<text font="3" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="928" width="360">rangement of data, especially one in which the data are ar-</text>
 
0	<text font="3" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="946" width="360">ranged in columns and rows in an essentially rectangular</text>
 
0	<text font="3" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="964" width="360">form. In addition, we add an additional restriction on the</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="983" width="360">deï¬nition of tables in scientiï¬c documents: each table has</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="1001" width="360">a caption that starts with a keyword (e.g., â€œTableâ€ or â€œTA-</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="1019" width="360">BLEâ€). With this restriction, the tables can be understood</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="478" textpieces="0" top="1037" width="360">as genuine tables [6]. The table boundary includes all the</text>
 
