0	<text font="9" height="13" left="120" textpieces="0" top="197" width="323">Different lines in the same page have different internal</text>
 
0	<text font="10" height="13" left="103" textpieces="0" top="214" width="340">space size, text density, and length. A document page con-</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="13" left="103" textpieces="0" top="232" width="340">tains at least one column and many have two (e.g., ACM and</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="13" left="103" textpieces="0" top="249" width="340">IEEE conference formats), or three even four columns. The</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="13" left="103" textpieces="0" top="266" width="340">length of lines can be equal to, longer (e.g., cross-column</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="13" left="103" textpieces="0" top="283" width="340">lines), or shorter (e.g., some headings) than the width of the</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="13" left="103" textpieces="0" top="300" width="340">document column. Because single-column documents are</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="13" left="103" textpieces="0" top="318" width="340">easy to process, in this paper, we focus on the most popular</text>
 
