0	<text font="9" height="13" left="103" textpieces="0" top="438" width="340">space gap between a pair of consecutive words within the</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="13" left="103" textpieces="0" top="455" width="340">line; 2) The length of this line is much shorter than a thresh-</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="13" left="103" textpieces="0" top="472" width="340">old ll; Note, different deï¬nitions of â€œlargeâ€ and the thresh-</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="13" left="103" textpieces="0" top="490" width="340">old ll generate different results. Based on the observation</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="13" left="103" textpieces="0" top="507" width="340">and the statistical results on thousands of table examples, in</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="13" left="103" textpieces="0" top="524" width="340">this paper we set the â€œlargeâ€ as the double of the average</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="13" left="103" textpieces="0" top="541" width="340">space between words in document body content lines, and</text>
 
0	<text font="10" height="13" left="103" textpieces="0" top="558" width="284">ll as the two third of the document column width;</text>
 
0	<text font="10" height="13" left="120" textpieces="0" top="576" width="323">Non-sparse lines, which satisfy neither of the conditions,</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="13" left="103" textpieces="0" top="593" width="340">usually occur in the following document components: long</text>
 
