0	<text font="13" height="11" left="255" textpieces="0" top="304" width="13">(a)</text>
 
0	<text font="13" height="11" left="255" textpieces="0" top="513" width="14">(b)</text>
 
0	<text font="12" height="14" left="105" textpieces="0" top="552" width="319">Figure 3. Two examples of the text sequence</text>
 
0	<text font="12" height="14" left="105" textpieces="0" top="570" width="43">errors</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="87" textpieces="0" top="622" width="355">tent ï¬rst, jump to another document area and process it, and</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="87" textpieces="0" top="640" width="355">then come back to ï¬nish the rest of the table sections. Such</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="87" textpieces="0" top="658" width="355">alternation happens at least once. Figure 3b shows an exam-</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="87" textpieces="0" top="676" width="355">ple: the text extraction tools output the table caption ï¬rst on</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="87" textpieces="0" top="694" width="355">the second document column, then jump to the ï¬rst docu-</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="87" textpieces="0" top="712" width="355">ment column on the left and process some scattered texts in</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="87" textpieces="0" top="730" width="355">the ï¬gures. After telling the ï¬gure caption, they come back</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="87" textpieces="0" top="748" width="355">to the table area. Sometimes, the tools extract several table</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="87" textpieces="0" top="766" width="355">columns then jump to other areas (e.g., the following regu-</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="87" textpieces="0" top="784" width="355">lar document contents) to ï¬nish several lines or paragraphs,</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="87" textpieces="0" top="802" width="355">then return to the table data again. With such beyond-table</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="87" textpieces="0" top="820" width="355">text sequence errors, collecting all the table cells is a chal-</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="87" textpieces="0" top="838" width="355">lenging task because it is difï¬cult to predict how far the</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="87" textpieces="0" top="856" width="246">distances are among different table parts.</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="105" textpieces="0" top="887" width="337">In order to accurately collect the table cells from a page</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="87" textpieces="0" top="905" width="355">and recover the sequence, resorting the texts in the page is</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="87" textpieces="0" top="922" width="355">one approach. B. Yildiz et. al mentioned the similar idea</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="87" textpieces="0" top="940" width="355">in [7] but without any detail about the methodology and the</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="87" textpieces="0" top="958" width="355">performance. Other proposed approaches [1] exploit geo-</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="87" textpieces="0" top="976" width="355">metric or typographic features of the page objects, and go</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="87" textpieces="0" top="994" width="355">further in exploiting the content of object. X-Y cut approach</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="87" textpieces="0" top="1012" width="355">is a representing method. However, its performance is not</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="87" textpieces="0" top="1030" width="355">satisfying. Moreover, these proposed works need to process</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="87" textpieces="0" top="1048" width="355">both sparse lines and non-sparse lines. The more non-sparse</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="87" textpieces="0" top="1066" width="286">lines involve, the higher possibility errors incur.</text>
 
=======================================COL========================================
0	<text font="11" height="16" left="476" textpieces="1" top="119" width="306">4  Text sequence recovering algorithms</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="493" textpieces="0" top="141" width="337">To ï¬x the text sequence error problem, we propose two</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="159" width="355">methods to resort the detected sparse lines within a given</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="177" width="355">area. For the inside-table text sequence errors, the area is</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="195" width="355">the table itself. For the beyond-table text sequence errors,</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="213" width="355">the area is the whole page. Some pages have multiple doc-</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="231" width="355">ument columns, whether considering such information or</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="249" width="355">not may generate different results for different cases. In</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="267" width="355">this paper, we try both of them and analyze their advan-</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="285" width="122">tages/disadvantages.</text>
 
0	<text font="14" height="15" left="476" textpieces="1" top="325" width="355">4.1  Algorithm 1: Considering the docu-</text>
 
0	<text font="14" height="15" left="519" textpieces="0" top="343" width="211">ment column information</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="493" textpieces="0" top="363" width="337">The recovering procedure includes two parts: the cross-</text>
 
0	<text font="10" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="381" width="355">column resorting, and the within-column resorting. Here</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="399" width="355">the column refers to the document column instead of the</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="417" width="355">table column. How to get the document column informa-</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="435" width="355">tion is out of scope of this paper. We adopt an easy but</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="453" width="355">effective method by calculating the average length of the</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="471" width="355">non-sparse lines then comparing with the document width.</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="489" width="355">For the inside-table text sequence disordering, we only im-</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="507" width="355">plement the within-column resorting. For the beyond-table</text>
 
0	<text font="10" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="525" width="355">text sequence disordering, we have to implement both re-</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="543" width="51">sortings.</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="493" textpieces="1" top="562" width="337">In the cross-column resorting,SL denotes the set of all</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="1" top="580" width="264">the sparse lines in a document page: SL =</text>
 
0	<text font="5" height="11" left="758" textpieces="0" top="575" width="11">m</text>
 
0	<text font="5" height="11" left="758" textpieces="1" top="587" width="72">i=1(li). For</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="2" top="598" width="355">a document columnCOk, its beginning and ending X-axes</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="5" top="616" width="355">values areXcok andXcok. Each column has a vectorv to</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="634" width="355">store its sparse lines. Initially, the vector is empty. For each</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="652" width="355">sparse line, we compare its X-axis coordinates with doc-</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="1" top="670" width="355">ument columns and append it in the matched vectorv, if</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="688" width="355">applicable. Some sparse lines may cross several document</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="706" width="355">columns. Such lines usually are lines in cross-column ta-</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="724" width="355">bles/ï¬gures or long document titles or afï¬liations, etc. We</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="1" top="742" width="232">record such lines in another vectorvcc.</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="493" textpieces="0" top="761" width="337">In the within-column resorting part, the inputs include</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="1" top="779" width="354">the ï¬lled vector V and Vcc. The output is a new vector</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="19" left="476" textpieces="0" top="793" width="355">Vsorted, which stores all sorted sparse lines. For each doc-</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="2" top="815" width="355">ument columnCOk, we get all the Y-axis values from the</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="2" top="833" width="355">sparse lines in vectorvk. Among these Y-axis values, we</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="851" width="355">identify all the non-duplicated values and sort them, and</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="1" top="869" width="354">store them in a new vectorVy. With these Y-axis values, we</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="2" top="887" width="355">sort all sparse lines in vectorvk accordingly. This method</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="905" width="355">works well for the tables that are located within one doc-</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="922" width="355">ument column (e.g., the table in Figure 3b). However, for</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="940" width="355">the wide tables that cross more than one document column</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="958" width="355">(see Figure 1a), this algorithm may generate errors because</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="976" width="355">it is difï¬cult to know which lines should cross the docu-</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="994" width="355">ment columns in advance. If there are overlaps between the</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="1012" width="355">table column spaces and the document column spaces, this</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="1030" width="355">method will segment a whole table into at least two parts.</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="1048" width="355">Although some table lines may block the document column</text>
 
0	<text font="9" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="1066" width="327">space, it is difï¬cult to identify the last line of the table.</text>
 
0	<text font="7" height="11" left="447" textpieces="0" top="1112" width="24">1008</text>
 
0	<text font="8" height="8" left="107" textpieces="0" top="1175" width="555">Authorized licensed use limited to: Penn State University. Downloaded on February 9, 2010 at 16:37 from IEEE Xplore.  Restrictions apply. </text>
 
