0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="457" width="360">of table captions, such as â€œTable, TABLE, Form, FORM,â€</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="475" width="360">etc. Each table caption starts with a keyword. If more than</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="494" width="360">one table is displayed together, the keyword is very useful</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="512" width="360">to separate the tables from each other. At the beginning, we</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="530" width="360">check all the lines (not only the sparse line) in a page. Once</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="548" width="360">we detect a line starting with a keyword, we treat it as a table</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="566" width="360">caption candidate. Then we check the subsequent sorted</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="585" width="360">sparse lines and merge them into a sparse area, according</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="603" width="360">to the vertical distance between the lines. Different table</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="621" width="360">captions provide different hints and restraints on whether</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="639" width="292">we include the cross-column sparse lines or not.</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="494" textpieces="0" top="661" width="342">If a table caption starts in the second document column</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="680" width="360">(e.g., the right table in Figure 2a), the table boundary can</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="698" width="360">not span the ï¬rst column. If a table caption satisï¬es one of</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="716" width="360">the following conditions, it is a cross-column table: 1) the</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="734" width="360">width of the table caption is larger than the document col-</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="753" width="360">umn width; 2) the starting X-axis value of the caption is on</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="771" width="360">the right of the midpoint of the ï¬rst document column. Once</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="789" width="360">we conï¬rm a table as a cross-column table, we treat each Y-</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="807" width="360">axis value as a table row. Otherwise, every table row can</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="825" width="360">only include the sparse lines within the current document</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="844" width="360">column. Because we will zoom in and analyze the detected</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="862" width="360">table boundary carefully in the later table structure decom-</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="880" width="360">position phase, we treat recall more importantly than preci-</text>
 
0	<text font="3" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="898" width="342">sion by accepting false positive table boundary contents.</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="494" textpieces="0" top="920" width="342">If a table caption is shorter than the document column</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="939" width="360">width, and its beginning position aligns with that of the ï¬rst</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="957" width="360">document column (see the table caption in Figure 1), it is</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="975" width="360">difï¬cult to judge whether this table a cross-column table or</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="993" width="360">not. For such a case, we assume it as a single-column table</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="1011" width="360">initially, after ï¬gure out the document column where the</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="1030" width="360">caption belongs to, we check the same Y-axis area in the</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="1048" width="360">next document column. If this area is also a sparse area, we</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="1066" width="360">merge the new area into the table boundary and treat this</text>
 
0	<text font="7" height="11" left="447" textpieces="0" top="1112" width="24">1009</text>
 
0	<text font="8" height="8" left="107" textpieces="0" top="1175" width="555">Authorized licensed use limited to: Penn State University. Downloaded on February 9, 2010 at 16:37 from IEEE Xplore.  Restrictions apply. </text>
 
