0	<text font="2" height="16" left="83" textpieces="1" top="185" width="220">5  Experiments and Results</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="101" textpieces="0" top="205" width="340">Our experiments can be divided into two parts: the eval-</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="0" top="223" width="358">uation of the text sequence recovering and the table bound-</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="0" top="241" width="358">ary detection. A ï¬ve-user study is implemented. Each user</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="0" top="259" width="358">checked the sequence of the resorted sparse lines in 20 se-</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="0" top="277" width="358">lected PDF pages. Half of them have within-table sequence</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="0" top="295" width="358">errors and the other half have beyond-table sequence errors.</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="2" top="313" width="359">The evaluation metric is pairwise accuracy. IfHRis the</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="2" top="331" width="359">sequence decided by human judgement andARis the se-</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="0" top="350" width="358">quence decided by the algorithms, the pairwise accuracy</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="0" top="368" width="358">can be deï¬ned as the fraction of times that our algorithms</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="0" top="386" width="358">and human judges agree on the sequence: pairwise accu-</text>
 
0	<text font="3" height="14" left="83" textpieces="0" top="406" width="41">racy =</text>
 
0	<text font="5" height="14" left="131" textpieces="1" top="399" width="52">|HRâˆ©AR|</text>
 
0	<text font="5" height="11" left="147" textpieces="0" top="414" width="18">HR</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="184" textpieces="0" top="406" width="257">. For algorithm 1, the correct sequence of</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="0" top="424" width="358">human judge is column by column. For algorithm 2, hu-</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="0" top="442" width="358">mans treat each page as a single-column page. Comparing</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="0" top="460" width="358">such â€œgolden standardâ€, the pairwise accuracy of both al-</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="0" top="478" width="358">gorithms are 100%. Still using the Figure 3a as the example,</text>
 
