0	<text font="4" height="14" left="101" textpieces="0" top="751" width="340">The evaluation metrics for the table boundary detection</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="1" top="769" width="359">are precisionP and recall R. Given the number of true ta-</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="1" top="787" width="359">ble lines in our detected table boundaryA, the number of</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="1" top="805" width="358">overlooked true positive table linesB, and the number of</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="2" top="823" width="318">misidentiï¬ed true negative non-table linesC, P = A</text>
 
0	<text font="5" height="11" left="382" textpieces="0" top="831" width="27">A+C</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="412" textpieces="0" top="823" width="29">, and</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="20" left="83" textpieces="1" top="840" width="41">R= A</text>
 
0	<text font="5" height="11" left="105" textpieces="0" top="853" width="28">A+B</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="135" textpieces="0" top="844" width="307">. The performance of two algorithms are listed in</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="1" top="862" width="358">Table 1. The reason forC are some non-table sparse lines</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="0" top="881" width="358">surrounding the table boundary. They usually also belong</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="0" top="899" width="358">to the table data.(e.g., the short lines of the table caption</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="0" top="917" width="358">and footnote). For single-column tables, Algorithm 2 may</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="1" top="935" width="358">have moreC because of the possible sparse lines with sim-</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="0" top="953" width="358">ilar Y-axis values in the next document column. Because</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="0" top="971" width="358">the widths of cells in single-column table can not be large</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="0" top="989" width="358">and the noise lines in table boundary can be easily removed</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="0" top="1007" width="358">in later table structure decomposition step, we prefer high</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="0" top="1026" width="358">recall values. For cross-column tables, algorithm 1 will cut</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="0" top="1044" width="358">each table into at least two parts. A merge postprocessing is</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="83" textpieces="0" top="1062" width="358">required. Algorithm 2 achieves better performance on such</text>
 
