0	<text font="2" height="16" left="476" textpieces="1" top="448" width="114">6  Conclusion</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="494" textpieces="0" top="467" width="340">In this paper, we analyze a typical problem shared by the</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="485" width="358">PDF text extraction tools: the text sequence error. We pro-</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="503" width="358">pose two algorithms to recover the sequence of extracted</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="522" width="358">sparse lines, which improve the table content collection.</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="540" width="358">The experimental results not only compare the performance</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="558" width="358">of both algorithms, but also demonstrate the effectiveness of</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="576" width="358">text sequence recovering for the table boundary detection.</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="594" width="358">The results show that the second algorithm achieves better</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="612" width="358">results for both single-column table and cross-column table.</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="630" width="358">It is proved that the text sequence recovering work plays a</text>
 
0	<text font="4" height="14" left="476" textpieces="0" top="648" width="294">crucial role in the table boundary detection ï¬eld.</text>
 
